  "prompt": "Does P = NP?",
  "response": "The question of whether \\( P = NP \\) is one of the most important open problems in computer science and mathematics. \n\nIn simple terms:\n- \\( P \\) (Polynomial Time) refers to the class of problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine in polynomial time.\n- \\( NP \\) (Nondeterministic Polynomial Time) refers to the class of problems for which a given solution can be verified in polynomial time.\n\nIf \\( P = NP \\), it would mean that every problem for which we can verify a solution quickly (in polynomial time) can also be solved quickly (in polynomial time). Conversely, if \\( P \\neq NP \\), it implies that there are problems that are easy to verify but hard to solve.\n\nAs of now, no one has been able to prove or disprove whether \\( P = NP \\). The Clay Mathematics Institute has designated this problem as one of the seven \"Millennium Prize Problems,\" offering a prize of one million dollars for a correct solution.\n\nResearch continues in this area, and it remains a fundamental question with deep implications in fields such as cryptography, algorithm design, and complexity theory.",
